[[Embedded Communications]]
# CAN and Automotive Applications
- Modern cars are loaded with many microcontrollers distributed across the vehicle to control various subsystems
- CAN was developed originally to interface these microcontrollers
# Physical Interface
- All devices on the CAN bus are connected on a single 2-wire differentially signaled bus
- Only one device can transmit at once
	- Half duplex
	- Requires MAC mechanism
- The cables form a twisted pair
- The ends of the bus must be terminated with a 120 Ohm resistor connecting CANH and CANL

# Detailed CAN Frame
![](data:image/png;base64,)
## Bit Timing
- CAN is asynchronous, so all devices on the bus must be configured to read at the same baud rate
## Stuff Bits
- If the line is held at the same logical value for too long (typically defined as 5 consecutive bits) the CAN Protocol will insert a stuff bit ( the dominant inverse ) to give the synchronization hardware a heartbeat
# CAN Framing
![](data:image/png;base64,)
## Start of Frame:
- Always logical 0
- Dominant value to pull bus out of recessive idle
## CAN IDs
- Each CAN frame starts with an ID field
	- 11 Bits in Standard CAN (baseID)
	- 29 Bits in Extended CAN
### CAN Arbitration (MAC)
- ![](data:image/png;base64,)
- High priority messages have lower values
- The CAN bus driver reads bits at the same time that it is trying to write bits
- As it transmits its ID bits, it will read the bus line
- If it detects that the line is at a logical 0 while it is trying to write a logical 1, it knows that there is a higher priority (lower value) message on the wire
- It will then back off and start reading
## The RTR Bit
- The RTR bit in the CAN header indicates whether a node sends data or requests data from another node
## IDE and r0 Bits
- Identifier extension: Dominant 0 for standard 11-bit IDs, recessive 1 for extended 29-bit frames
- r0 Reserved bit held at dominant 0 in classical CAN
## Control Bits
- DLC (Data length code): Specifies number of bytes (0-8) included in the frame's payload
## Data bits
- 0-8 byte payload
## CRC
- In classical CAN, the field is 15 bits followed by a 1-bit CRC delimiter (always recessive)
- CRC is calculated by the CAN controller, not performed or checked in software
## ACK Bits
- ACK Bit
	- Sent as a recessive bit by the tx, but any receiver that successfully receives the frame overwrites it with a dominant bit to acknowledge connection
- ACK delimiter
	- Always recessive bit that follows the ACK slot
	- Provides separation between ACK field and EOF
	- Ensures no node drives the bus during the EOF
## EOF bits
- Holds 7 consecutive recessive bits (logical 1) to mark the end
- Ensures all nodes recognize the frame has completed
- No node can transmit a dominant bit during the EOF field
- After EOF, bus remains recessive for at least 3 additional intermission bits before the next frame may begin
